TOPIC 16: BELIEFS GENERATE EXPERIENCES (NOT THE OTHER WAY AROUND)

The Confusion About Negative Experiences

• "How about anything negative outside? When I feel bad, something happens outside."

The Truth

• When you feel bad, it's because you believe that your relationship to that circumstance is defined in a negative way
• Redefine your relationship to the circumstance and you will not feel bad
• This is not saying to ignore the feeling

All Emotions Come From Beliefs

• All emotions without exception
• All emotions, all feelings
• Only exist because there is a belief that exists FIRST
• You CANNOT have a feeling without having a definition or a belief first

The Self-Investigation Process

When you have a bad feeling:

1. **Acknowledge it**
   - "All right, I've got a bad feeling. So what?"

2. **Ask yourself if you prefer this feeling**
   - "Do I prefer this feeling? Well, no. I would prefer something else. I would prefer to feel joyful."

3. **Ask why you had this bad feeling**
   - "Why did I have this bad feeling? What brought this about?"

4. **Remember feelings come from beliefs**
   - "I know that feelings come from beliefs. Oh, all right."

5. **Identify the belief**
   - "What kind of belief would I have to have about my relationship to this situation in order for me to have a bad feeling about it?"

6. **Begin the process of self-investigation**
   - Finding out what the definition is
   - Identifying it
   - Finding out why you had it
   - Letting that go
   - Changing it for something else you would prefer as a belief

7. **The cascade effect**
   - When you change the belief for one you prefer
   - That belief will generate a feeling that you prefer
   - Which will also generate thoughts that you prefer
   - Which will also generate behavior that you prefer

The "It's Not That Easy" Belief

• If you try this and say "it's not that easy"
• That's a belief
• Now the question is: Why do I have a belief that says it's not that easy?
• You can always take the question to the next level

Going Deeper

• If it doesn't seem to be working for you
• Look at the essence of what you're actually saying
• What's the result? "This is difficult. It's not that easy."
• You've now arrived at another place where you have something to work with
• Acknowledge it: "All right. I acknowledge that I have a feeling it's difficult."
• That must mean: "I have a belief that it's not easy."
• Why do I have that belief?
• Start the investigation again
• Keep doing that until you truly find the true fundamental foundational underlying belief that is generating all the other secondary level beliefs

Experience Does Not Generate Belief

• Common misconception: "I think it's not a belief but an experience"
• THE TRUTH: Your experience comes from your belief
• You can say "Well, that happened to me and so that's why I feel this way"
• But you are putting the cart before the horse
• The way you've been taught to look at reality makes you think that comes from the experience
• But in fact the experience first came from the belief

How Experience Reinforces Belief

• Once you have the experience, the experience may REINFORCE the belief
• But it doesn't GENERATE the belief
• The belief generates the experience
• Which then by definition strengthens the belief

Why Beliefs Seem So Real

• All beliefs must by definition contain an element, a component that is:
  - Self-generating
  - Self-fulfilling aspect
• If beliefs did not make it seem as if no other beliefs were possible
• You wouldn't be able to have that particular experience

The Cycle

• When you have a belief that generates an experience
• The experience will then always have the capacity to:
  - Reinforce the belief
  - Make it seem to be the only thing that's true
• But that's not true

Getting to the Point of Knowing

• You have to get to a point where you know it's not true
• No matter how it feels
• So that when something happens, you can recognize:
  - The experience is not causing the belief
  - It's just reinforcing the belief
  - Therefore, the experience can be used to put you in touch with the belief that generated the experience to begin with

There Is No Outside

• Even when something comes from another person (like a husband)
• "There is no outside"
• All the things you choose to feel, you choose to feel
• Anyone could come up to you and say anything
• You could still laugh
• Even if someone slaps you, you still have to choose how you feel

You're Choosing - It's Under Your Control

• The point is, you're choosing
• Which means it's under your control
• If you are choosing to feel bad, you have to ask yourself:
• "Why would I choose that?"
• When you ask that kind of question, it can put you in touch with the belief that makes you think that's your only choice
• When in fact you have many choices of how to feel and how to believe
• You have to find out why you're choosing what you're choosing

Learn to Appreciate Yourself More

• You must learn to appreciate yourself more
• This is the foundation

